{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Hedges et al. (2010) roughly suggested that at least 40 studies need to be synthesized for valid results, as synthesizing less studies may lead to underestimated standard errors and inflated type-1 error rates (see also Tipton, 2015).",
    "However, depending on the research questions that need to be addressed, it is often not feasible to identify and retrieve so many studies.",
    "Therefore, small-sample corrections have been developed for RVE that are based on applying the Satterthwaite correction to the degrees of freedom of model coefficient tests, so that the risk of a type-1 error rate in small sample meta-analyses decreases (Tipton, 2015; Tipton & Pustejovsky, 2015).",
    "However, it was found that these methods may still suffer from inflated type-1 error rates or from below-nominal type-1 error rates (Joshi et al., 2022; Tipton & Pustejovsky, 2015);.",
    "For specifically multiple-comparison tests, Tipton and Pustejovsky (2015) showed that small sample corrections (and the \"HTZ\" test in particular) may have low statistical power."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Hedges et al. (2010) roughly suggested that at least 40 studies need to be synthesized for valid results, as synthesizing less studies may lead to underestimated standard errors and inflated type-1 error rates (see also Tipton, 2015).",
    "Therefore, small-sample corrections have been developed for RVE that are based on applying the Satterthwaite correction to the degrees of freedom of model coefficient tests, so that the risk of a type-1 error rate in small sample meta-analyses decreases (Tipton, 2015; Tipton & Pustejovsky, 2015).",
    "However, it was found that these methods may still suffer from inflated type-1 error rates or from below-nominal type-1 error rates (Joshi et al., 2022; Tipton & Pustejovsky, 2015);.",
    "For specifically multiple-comparison tests, Tipton and Pustejovsky (2015) showed that small sample corrections (and the \"HTZ\" test in particular) may have low statistical power."
